# Scripted active-card puzzle: Stone Rain (land destruction).
#
# Stone Rain is a 2R sorcery that destroys target land. The script forces P0 to
# cast it at P1's Forest. After resolution the destroyed Forest leaves P1's
# battlefield and enters P1's graveyard (CR 701.7 destroy -> put into graveyard).
#
# NOTE on the setup: P0 pays {2}{R} with three Mountains; P1's land is a FOREST
# so the `targeting Forest` selector is unambiguous by name (there is exactly
# one Forest on the board, and it belongs to P1). If P1's land were also a
# Mountain the name matcher could not tell it apart from P0's own Mountains.
#
# A land is not a creature, so this is asserted purely with zone predicates,
# not the `creature died` event.
#
# Aspects exercised (tracking issue: Card Compatibility: Stone Rain):
#   - parses + castable as a 2R sorcery (spell cast)
#   - Land-restricted targeting (ValidTgts$ Land) resolves
#   - Destroy effect moves the land battlefield -> graveyard

[metadata]
Name:Action Script - Stone Rain Destroys a Land
Goal:Win
Turns:1
Difficulty:Easy
Description:P0 is driven by an action script that casts Stone Rain at one of P1's Mountains, destroying it. The Mountain moves from P1's battlefield to P1's graveyard. Demonstrates scripted active land destruction.

[state]
turn=1
activeplayer=p0
activephase=MAIN1
p0life=20
p0hand=Stone Rain
p0battlefield=Mountain;Mountain;Mountain
p0library=Forest;Forest;Forest;Forest;Forest

p1life=20
p1battlefield=Forest
p1library=Mountain;Mountain;Mountain;Mountain;Mountain

[p0_script]
# Cast Stone Rain at the opponent's Forest (the only Forest on the board, so the
# name selector is unambiguous and picks P1's land, not P0's Mountains).
cast Stone Rain targeting Forest

[assertions]
# The land-destruction spell was actually cast by the script (active-card aspect).
spell cast Stone Rain
# The destroyed Forest is now in its owner's (P1's) graveyard. (Assertions are
# evaluated on the FINAL game state after the game plays out; a destroyed
# permanent stays in the graveyard, so this is a stable end-state check. A
# battlefield-count check is NOT used here because the opponent keeps playing
# lands on its own turns, so its battlefield is not empty at game end.)
opponent graveyard contains Forest
